---
import PageLayout from "@layouts/PageLayout.astro"
import TopLayout from "@layouts/TopLayout.astro"
import BottomLayout from "@layouts/BottomLayout.astro"
import { ABOUT } from "@consts"
---

<PageLayout title={ABOUT.TITLE} description={ABOUT.DESCRIPTION}>
  <TopLayout>
    <div class="animate page-heading">
      {ABOUT.TITLE}
    </div>
  </TopLayout>
  <BottomLayout>
    <div class="animate">
      <article>

        <p>
          I'm Zijian — currently an MSc FinTech student at The Hong Kong Polytechnic University,
          preparing for PhD applications in AI, robotics, and agentic systems.
          But this page is not about my CV. It's about the person behind the research.
        </p>

        <h2>Systems as Thinking Infrastructure</h2>

        <p>
          I've spent years building personal productivity systems with tools like
          <b>Obsidian</b> and <b>Notion</b>. I don't treat them as aesthetic dashboards —
          I treat them as <b>thinking infrastructure</b>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Important ideas rarely arrive fully formed. They begin as fragments: project notes,
          paper summaries, experiment observations, questions, and half-finished reflections.
          If those fragments aren't captured and revisited, they disappear before they can
          become useful.
        </p>

        <p>
          For research, this matters. A good system helps me:
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>separate observations from conclusions;</li>
          <li>track why an experiment failed;</li>
          <li>connect concepts across finance, AI, and robotics;</li>
          <li>preserve questions that may become future research ideas;</li>
          <li>review long-term goals without losing sight of weekly execution.</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          The point is not to become more busy. The point is to become more <b>coherent</b>.
        </p>

        <h2>Sport and Research Discipline</h2>

        <p>
          I train consistently — <b>tennis twice a week</b> and <b>Hyrox-style conditioning</b>
          have become part of how I maintain energy, patience, and resilience.
        </p>

        <p>
          Sport gives feedback that is difficult to avoid. If my movement is late, the ball is gone.
          If my conditioning is weak, the workout exposes it. If I become emotional, my execution
          becomes worse.
        </p>

        <p>
          That feedback loop is useful for research temperament. It teaches me to respect
          fundamentals, stay calm under pressure, and improve through repeated small corrections.
        </p>

        <p>
          Research has a similar rhythm. A model fails. A proof doesn't close. A result
          looks promising and then collapses under a better validation split. The useful
          response is not panic — it's <b>diagnosis</b>.
        </p>

        <h2>History, Philosophy, and Long-term Thinking</h2>

        <p>
          Outside technical work, I'm drawn to <b>Chinese history and philosophy</b>.
          Part of the attraction is scale. Historical thinking makes individual problems
          feel less absolute. It reminds me that systems, incentives, institutions, and
          human behavior interact over long periods.
        </p>

        <p>
          That perspective matters for AI and finance. Models don't exist in empty space.
          They operate inside social, economic, and institutional environments. A technically
          impressive system can still fail if it ignores incentives, feedback loops, or
          human behavior.
        </p>

        <p>
          Philosophy also helps me think about ambition. I want to work seriously, but not
          frantically. I want to build competence over years, not only chase short bursts
          of performance.
        </p>

        <h2>Why This Matters for a PhD</h2>

        <p>
          A PhD is not only a test of whether someone can understand difficult ideas. It is
          also a test of whether they can return to a problem again and again, organize
          uncertainty, recover from failed attempts, and keep improving without needing
          immediate reward.
        </p>

        <p>
          My systems, sport, and humanities interests all point toward the same underlying trait:
          I care about <b>sustained development</b>. I'm learning to become someone who can hold
          a difficult question for a long time, keep records honestly, train consistently, and
          return to the work with more clarity each time.
        </p>

        <p>
          That, to me, is part of becoming a researcher.
        </p>

      </article>

      <div class="mt-12 pt-6 border-t border-black/10 dark:border-white/25">
        <a href="/" class="group flex gap-1.5 items-center text-sm hover:text-black dark:hover:text-white transition-colors duration-300 ease-in-out">
          <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="stroke-current">
            <line x1="19" y1="12" x2="5" y2="12" class="scale-x-0 group-hover:scale-x-100 translate-x-3 group-hover:translate-x-0 transition-all duration-300 ease-in-out" />
            <polyline points="12 19 5 12 12 5" class="translate-x-1 group-hover:translate-x-0 transition-all duration-300 ease-in-out" />
          </svg>
          <span>Back to home</span>
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </BottomLayout>
</PageLayout>
